<section xml:id="topic-3-1-abstraction">
  <title>Abstraction and Program Design</title><introduction>
    
    <p>In Unit 1, we learned to use <term>classes</term> and <term>objects</term> that are built-in to
            Java or written by other programmers, for example the <c>Turtle</c> class. In this unit, you will learn to write your
            own classes and make your own objects! Prior to implementing a class, it is helpful to take time to design each class including its attributes and behaviors. This design can be represented using natural language or diagrams. In this lesson, you will learn about abstraction and how it can be used to design a program.</p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
            <title>Object-Oriented Design</title>
            <p>In <term>object-oriented design</term> (OOD), programmers often start by deciding which classes are needed to solve a problem and then figure out the data and methods in each class.</p>
            <p>When you are given a problem specification, you can identify classes you’ll need
                by looking for the <term>nouns</term> in the specification. For instance, the
                specification for the Turtle class probably contained a
                sentence that said something like, “make turtles that can exist on a
                2-dimensional world and can draw lines by moving around the world”. The main
                nouns in that description are “turtle” and “world” and indeed the classes in the
                system are <c>Turtle</c> and <c>World</c>.</p>

